observations.recommendation:
We strongly reiterated our prior years’ recommendations that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

a. Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile at the end of each month their bank account records, and effect the necessary adjustment to avoid accumulation thereof and come up with the correct balance of the Cash in Bank-LCCA account in their respective records;

b. Municipal Accountant to verify and evaluate the accuracy of the reconciling items reflected in the BRS and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to come up with the adjusted balance of the Cash in Bank-LCCA account;

c. Municipal Treasurer to make representation with the depository banks and formally request for copies of the debit/credit memos to support adjustment in the books; and

d. Municipal Treasurer to immediately locate and submit to the Municipal Accounting Office the disbursement vouchers for proper recording in the Municipality’s books. Otherwise, any unjustified failure on the part of the official concerned to submit the required reports/documents shall be considered a ground for the automatic suspension of payment of her salaries until she shall have complied therewith without prejudice to any disciplinary action that may be instituted against her, pursuant to Section 122 of PD No. 1445 (The Government Auditing Code of the Philippines).

We strongly reiterated our previous years’ recommendations that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

a. Inventory Committee to conduct a physical count of supplies/inventories and to expedite the completion of the inventory of PPE and submit thereon to the Auditor, in proper form, summarized according to type of PPE and properly accomplished in all particulars, in accordance with Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I. Further, the inventory report should be reconciled with the Accounting and GSO records. Any discrepancies found should be investigated, and the necessary adjustments should be made where the error was committed;

b. Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of the Road Network System of the Municipality and prepare and submit the required report thereon, in proper form as required under Item VI of COA Circular No. 2015-008;

c. OIC-GSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete and updated PCs and PPELCs, respectively;

d. Municipal Accountant and the OIC-GSO to locate the related documents on damaged properties razed by fire as guide for Management on what proper action to be undertaken to drop the cost of the same from the books of accounts of the Municipality;

e. Municipal Engineer to expedite the submission of the complete description and cost segregation of the road components for road projects of the Municipality;

f. OIC-GSO to maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete LRNPC for all roads and its components; and

g. Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system of the Municipality at year-end.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee to submit immediately the inventory report to the Office the Auditor for verification. Conduct a physical count of the Municipality’s properties annually and observe strictly the prescribed date of submission of the RPCPPE to the Auditor pursuant to Section 124 of the MNGAS, Volume 1. Likewise, proper reconciliation between  the inventory report and the records maintained by the GSO and Accounting Office, respectively, should be made. Any discrepancies found should be investigated, and the necessary adjustments should be made where the error was committed;
b. Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entry to correct the overstatement of recording of depreciation  expense  of P1,119,866.96 in the SEF books;
c. Municipal Accountant and GSO to locate the related documents on  damaged properties razed by fire as guide for Management on what _proper action to_be undertaken to drop the cost of the same from the books of accounts of the Municipality; and
We also reiterated our recommendations that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

a. Office of the Municipal Accountant to continue exerting efforts in tracing back prior years’ acquisition of PPE to have complete detail of the fixed asset accounts so that corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the true value of the depreciable ~ fixed  asset accounts;
b. Property Officer/GSO prepare  Inventory  and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to account all unserviceable and obsolete items/properties previously taken up in the books as assets so that they may be properly disposed of and dropped from the accounts. Moreover, the disposal of property shall be made in accordance  with COA Circular No. 89-296 dated January 27, 1989; and
c. Property Officer/GSO to make certain that Property Cards are well- maintained, complete and updated to facilitate the physical count of property and equipment.

We reiterated our recommendations that the Municipal Mayor:
a. send through its Legal Office, demand letters to all officials and employees and those who are already out of government service who have unsettled obligations to the Municipal Government to liquidate their cash advances;
b. consider also filing appropriate charges against erring employees to compel compliance thereof;
c. undertake all available remedies under the above COA Circular to enforce settlement of the unliquidated cash advances and if necessary, order the withholding of the salaries and other emoluments of the existing officials/employees who continuously ignore, fail or refuse to comply with the demand to liquidate their outstanding cash advances; and
d. consider requesting for authority to write-off of the unliquidated cash advances of accountable officials who are already dead or could no longer be located, or if the settlement/liquidation is already impossible from the Commission on Audit pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005. Henceforth, see to it that the above-cited regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, particularly the period within which to liquidate the same are strictly and continuously enforced to protect the government funds from the risk of possible loss through misuse or misappropriation.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to analyze the accounts of the Accountable Officers with abnormal balances to effect the necessary adjustment thereof, for fair presentation of affected account in the financial statements.

We reiterated our recommendations that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all inventory items and prepare and submit to the Audit Team the corresponding RPCI, to substantiate the balance of Inventory accounts in _the financial statements;
b. GSO/Acting ~ Supply Officer to submit to the Accounting Office, the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued together with the copies of the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) and/or Distribution List duly acknowledged by the recipients, to support the recording/closing of the inventory accounts to the respective expense accounts;
c. GSO/Acting ~ Supply Officer to maintain a complete and accurate stock card for all supplies inventory in their custody to account for the acquisition, custody and issuance of the same; and
d. Municipal Accountant to adhere strictly to the provisions of Section 51 of the MNGAS for LGUs, on the proper recording and reporting of all regular purchases of supplies including drugs and medicines as Inventory account and maintenance of subsidiary ledger cards. That she shall also see to it that all donated supplies and materials particularly drugs and medicines received are properly accounted and recorded in the books of the Municipality; and
e. Designated Supply and Property Officer/Municipal Pharmacist, in-charge of medical supplies and materials, to prepare and maintain stock cards for control and monitoring purposes.

